is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"marriage","header":"Married Governor Talcott's daughter Eunice","body":"Eunice Talcott was the second daughter of Joseph Talcott, Governor of Connecticut from 1725 to 1741. Their marriage directly joined the two founding Hartford families — reinforced when Eunice's brother Matthew simultaneously married Mary Russell, herself a Hooker descendant."},{"number":2,"category":"legacy","header":"Named co-heir in the Governor's estate","body":"On December 25, 1742, Nathaniel and Eunice appeared before the Court of Probate in Hartford to sign Governor Joseph Talcott's estate distribution as co-heirs. It was one of the final official acts binding the Hooker family to the colonial governor's wealth."},{"number":3,"category":"career","header":"Yale man, militia captain, Assembly representative","body":"He graduated Yale College in 1729 and held the rank of Captain in the Connecticut Militia as early as 1734. He served as Hartford's representative in the General Assembly across three sessions, while running a substantial Hartford mercantile estate."},{"number":4,"category":"family","header":"Son James partnered in Hooker & Chaffee","body":"His son James Hooker was a partner in the mercantile firm Hooker & Chaffee, which grew very successful during the Revolutionary War era. The firm continued the family's Hartford commercial standing into the next generation."}],"baptism":{"year":1710,"month":10,"day":8,"city":"Hartford","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST022","institution_blurb":"Yale College 1729.","relationship":"alumnus","years":"1729"}],"education":[{"school_name":"Yale College","graduation_year":1729,"institution_id":"INST022"}],"bio":{"display_name":"Captain Nathaniel Hooker","first_name":"Nathaniel","last_name":"Hooker","title":"Captain","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"nathaniel-hooker-1710"},"I00054":{"id":"I00054","classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":true,"generation_from_john_talcott":3,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1709,"month":1,"day":26,"city":"Hartford","county":"Hartford County","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1795,"month":7,"day":12,"city":"Windsor","county":"Hartford County","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"parents":{"father_id":"T00045","mother_id":"U00017"},"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"H00115","location_city":"Hartford","location_state":"Connecticut","location_country":"United States","end_type":"death","end_year":1763,"children_ids":["H00346","H00347","H00348","H00349","H00350"]}],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entry 115"}],"talcott_book_id":"69","burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM107"},"cross_connections":[{"type":"founding_family_nexus","related_id":"H00356","display_label":"Sister-in-law — Mary Russell married her brother Matthew Talcott.","link_text":"Mary Russell Talcott"}],"gender":"female","tags":["hooker_talcott_convergence"],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"She and brother Matthew both married Hooker descendants","body":"She married Captain Nathaniel Hooker — a direct Hooker-surname descendant. Her brother Matthew Talcott simultaneously married Mary Russell, herself a Hooker descendant through the Pierpont line. Two of Governor Joseph Talcott's children marrying into the Hooker family in the same generation is why \"Talcott\" became a permanent name in the Hooker tree."}],"bio":{"display_name":"Eunice Talcott Hooker","first_name":"Eunice","last_name":"Hooker","maiden_name":"Talcott","married_names"